purely cosmetic.  The only reason I'm letting it go is b/c I have been able to use the friend of a friend network and have a chance to build my dream rifle at cost which will allow me to make every heavy buffer.  I've shot several DI and piston AR's in .308 and it's not even a contest this is the softest recoil I've shot, but it mostly due to the buffer not the gas system.  Used in tandem with this muzzle brake as long as you shoulder the weapon properly you won't lose sight of the target at recoil it's ready stays on target which is key for fast follow up shots in the woods on quick hogs.  The first one is always a head shot, but dang those hogs can scoot once they hear gunfire.  For the range accuracy crowd speed of reaquisition isn't that important, but for a hog hunter it's paramount.   The Ballistic Advantage barrel is right up there with Krieger for accuracy in my experience.  I've only taken this out to 360 yards which is as long as our range goes, but am able to routinely hit the 4" popper leaning off the hood of my truck which is still right at 1MOA at that distance(using PMC Bronze 147g).  At 100 yards off a bench with 175g Federal Match it's sub MOA even with a hot barrel *if* you have some good mechanics.  This rifle will be capable of all the accuracy you need unless it's F class competition.  The KeyMod handguard has a 2" pic rail section on the right for adding a green light or whatever and a swivel stud on the left for a sling.  I will include a standard USGI web sling with metal hardware, swivel stud front mount and QD rear mount.  I'm title: For Sale:  M1 Garand, WW2 correct, good barrel
postcontent:
U.S. Rifle, Cal. .30 M1, Springfield Armory, 3360033           
This rifle is an 80% parts correct WW2 M1 Garand. This rifle is a valuable combination of historic WW2 period rifle and accurate shooter - ready for service rifle competitions. It has a solid and tight stock, and new barrel installed at Springfield Armory at the end of its military service.
This rifle, serial number 3360033, first built to fight World War Two in late 1944 at the National Armory in Springfield Massachusetts (not the same as the modern gun company of the same name). The Springfield Armory came out with the highest quality M1 Rifles every year since they started making them in 1937.
This rifle, as probably 98% of all M1s in existence today, has been rebuilt at a government armory. This one was rebuilt in 1965 and bears the mark “SA” made in electric pencil on the receiver under the wood to prove it. This is back when rifles were works of art; not Legos that are simply snapped together (M4s). Even though this rifle has been rebuilt it is still a nearly parts correct rifle! For it’s serial number range it has the correct manufacture – style - marking on trigger group and bolt, and correct WW2 gas lock. The op-rod is a Springfield style from even earlier in WW2 than the rifle. It has a correct WW2 sight cover. The only significant parts not from WW2 are the rear sight mechanisms and barrel.
You can see plenty of dings in the wood. This rifle may or may not have seen oversees service but if you have spent one day in the military or even just seen a war movie, you know that a wooden rifle stock would get banged up. However, this wood is solid, it has no structural damage and fits the rifle tight. This stock has a rich red color in the walnut as well as the typical dings from service in the field. I have refinished a couple old U.S. Military rifle stocks and with a little de-greaser, fine steel wool, and a fresh coat of linseed oil (the original finish) the walnut stock will look brand new (if that is the look you want).
I could not get a good photo of the rifling, but it is there! The barrel has been used but is in excellent condition. With a gauge the muzzle reads a 1+ and the throat reads a 2 – that means nearly new. The finish is Parkerization (as all M1s are) and it is in good condition. The Gas Cylinder is stainless steel (as they all were) and for that reason it is painted. Springfield didn't have a good high temperature finish for stainless steel so they experimented with many kinds of black coatings.
Included in this deal is an empty eight round enblock clip, and a rifle case specially made for M1s by CMP.
Why am I selling it? Well, it takes two hands to shoot a rifle like this, and there is another rifle I would rather put in my hands.
 
Remember, General Patton called the M1 the, "Greatest Battle implement ever devised."
 
            "This is my M1 Garand Rifle, there are many like it, but this one is mine."
           
Email me for more photos, I also have a photo of a shot grouping (no accuracy guarantees for the rifle)
            Sorry, not interested in trades.
            I will ship from and to an FFL.
